{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868910/1930121901/0303.xml":{"full_text":"Mr. President: In this series oF open letters we have repeat\nedly asked you to urge congress to authorize a Liberty Loan for the\nJobless. We have suggested that a fund of from one to five billion\ndollars so obtained be used in a nation-wide public highway project.\nFrankly, this plan was proposed as an emergency measure in\norder that millions of unemployed may be enabled immediately to\nearn food and clothing.\nWe have asked for legislation because American business by\nitself seems unwilling to, do anything worth while to alleviate the\npresent chaos.\nAnd now, Mr. President, there are unmistakable signs every\nwhere that American business is taking advantage of the present\ndeplorable situation to beat workers down to lower standards in\nthe scale of life!\nReports reach us that wage cuts and all sorts of devices are\nbeing employed to smash the confidence and self-respect of those\nwho still have jobs. Such as, for instance, the case of powerful\nrailroad companies where the employes are required to contribute\none day\u2019s pay per month for the relief of their unemployed brothers.\nPoverty is the open-mouthed,\nrelentless hell which yawns be\nneath civilized society.\u2014Henry\nGeorge.\nVol. 20\u2014No. 11.\nOKLAHOMA OIL BLAZE PERILS TOWN\nHOME BUILDING\n580,000,000\nLOWERINYEAR\nHoover Planning\nCommittee Starts\nToward Its Goal.\nBl CECIL OWEN.\nStaff* Correspondent\nThe United Press\nW A SHINGTO N\u2014Home dwellers\nIn Ihe United States were estimat\ned :it more than 20,1'00,000 families,\n<>r about 80 per cent of the popula\ntion, as President Hoover's home\nplanning committee today moved to\nward its goal of making this a na\ntion oJ home owners.\nAppointment of 16 new commit\ntees to study various phases of\nhouie making and ownership was\nannounced by the main committee\nof which Secretary of Commerce\nLamont is chairman. These sub\ngroups will study every aspect of\nhome making\nFigures Reflect Slump.\nFigures made public by the com\nmittee showed a .triking decrease\nin residential construction this year\ncompared with 1929, when nearly\n$2,000,000,000 in new residences\nwere built.\nIn comparison, residential build\ning dropped off to $1,020,000,000 this\nyear, a decrease of 43 per cent.\nConference Next Fall.\nThe committee is pushing its\nJ< during this slack period in the\njactation it will have plans\n\"eady for model home construction,\nwhen business revival rgain causes\nresumption of home buildii j on a\nlarge scale.\nNext fall, a general conference\nwill bp held here at which the sub\ncommittee will report their findings.\nAPPEAL FROM\nCM RULING\nIS NOW FILED\nNEWARK, N. J. The United\nStates government\u2019s appeal from\nhe ruling of Judge William Clark,\nhat the ISth amendment is invalid,\n\u2022ecause it was ratified by the legis\na lures of the several states, in\ntend of by the people in conven\nion, was tiled here yesterday less\nhan 4S hours after it had been\nlanded down.\nIt is to go direct to the supreme\nourt of the United States in Wash\nigton for early adjudication. The\nppeal automatically stays th\" el\nect of the decision until, Ihe su\nreme court has passed on it.\nWhile Philip Forman. Umted\nfates attorney, was busy putting\nis appeal order and petition\ntrough, the prohibition authorities\ni New Jersey continued their\nlids, descending on an alleged\nteakeasy in Morristown am! a\n500-gallon still in Bloomfield.\nEarly Ruling Expected.\nWASHINGTON\u2014The decision of\nedge Clark of New Jersey, holding\nie 18th amendment invalid, may\npassed upon by the supreme\nmrt at its present term.\nCourt attaches said the govern\ntent\u2019s appeal, allowed yesterday,\nrobably would reach the court\nion. particularly if the record,\nhi< h must accompany it, should\n3 short\nit will he docketed immediately\nTuiu to Tage Seven, Column One.\nLIBERTY LOAN FOR THE JOBLESS\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nSenate Delays Millions for Jobless Aid\nGlaring Fraud Shown\nIn Racket Methods\nOn Jobless Victim\nM\nTricks which unscrupulous high\npressure salesmen use to trap un\nwary unemployed men and women\nare illustrated in the case of the\nNational Salesmen\u2019s Training Assn.,\nChicago, against Paul Idefer, a\nsheet metal worker, which was\npending 'in local courts for more\nthan a year.\nWhile some of the facts in this\ncase were reported in The Milwau\nkee Leader at the time Circuit\nJudge Charles L. Aarons dismissed\nthe case with caustic comment, The\nLeader feels that they will stand\nrepetition in the present series of\narticles exposing the operations of\nslickers.\nAd Is the Bait.\nIn March, 1927, an ad appeared\nin one of the local non-partisan\nnewspaper\u2019s Help Wanted column\nas follows:\n\u201cIf you are out of work and want\na job. write to ^ox Chicago.\u201d\nPaul Liefer, out of work and al\nmost penniless, .answered the ad. A\nCOPS HOLD 4\nOF 1 FAMILY\nAS SUSPECTS\nMilwaukee police today were\nbolding four members of the family\nof Jack O\u2019Neil, 37 years old, who\nWednesday night was argued out of\nbolding up John Jledl\u2019s roadhouse,\nCedarburg and Brown Deer roads.\nThey were picked up yesterday\nalter S3OO, which is said to have\nbeen taken Wednesday by O'Neil in\na hold-up of Louis Wagner\u2019s grocery\nstore at Mequon, was found in a\nwoodpile in the rear of their home\non the Cedarburg road near High\nway 100.\nTo Check Mentality.\nO\u2019Neil late yesterday was hound\nover to municipal court for trial on\ncharge of assault and robbery. He\nwill be given a mental examination.\nThe other three held, who are\nalleged to have plotted or partici\npated in the robbery of Wagner\u2019s\nstore are Mr. and Mrs. Frank\nHeiple and their 21-year-old daugh\nter. Elva O\u2019Neil.\nThey will be turned over to\nOzaukee count,v authorities.\nO'Neil's police record shows sev\neral ,i previous crimes and three\naliases.\nUsed Three Aliases\nUnder the names of Jack Murphy.\nJack Green ami Jack Carey he was\nsentenced in Columbus. Ohio, from\none to five years for jiocket picking\nin 1919; he was given 18 months\nfor a box car burglary in Atlanta\nin 1921: he was sentenced from two\nto 15 years for assault with intent\nto rob in Loraine. Ohio, in 1928.\nHe was last released from prison\nJi 15. 1930.\nItalian Sea Fliers\nDelayed by Storms\nROME\u2014The departure of 12 Ital\nian seaplanes from Palma, Island\nof Majorca, and Cartagena. Spain,\non the second leg of their proposed\nflight to South America was de\nlayed again by storms today, ad\nvices received here said.\nOpen Letter to President Hoover\u2014No. 9\nfew days later two salesmen of the\nhigh-pressure va^ety called upon\nhim and tried to sell him a course\nin salesmanship.\n\u201cWe received your letter and we\nhave a job for you right now,\u201d the\nsalesmen said, according to Liefer.\n\u201cWe will fix you up so that you\ncan start work tomorrow morning,\nbut you will have to be trained for\nthe job and take this course.\n\u201cWe will guarantee that you will\nget the job.\u201d\nSeparated From $lO.\nLiefe.- finally agreed after much\nargument along these lines and was\nasked to make a first payment of\n$25 on the salesmanship correspond\nence course offered by the \u201cassocia\ntion.\u201d\n\u201cWe'll make an exception for you\nin this case and let you make a first\npayment of only $10,\u201d and the\nsalesmen took the money, at the\nsame time getting Liefer\u2019s signature\nto what Liefer thought was merely\nTurn to Page Four, Column Fou\u00a3.\nMore Snow Tonight,\nColeman Forecast\nLight snow will fall in Milwaukee\ntonight and temperatures wjll range\nfrom 27 to 36 degrees, according to\nFrank H. Coleman, weather ob\nserver. Tomorrow will be partly\ncloudy with a possibility of snow\nflurries.\nFOUR MILLION\nESTATE GIVEN\nTO CHARITIES\nNEW YORK\u2014Fifteen charitable\nand educational institutions, chosen\nby Alfred E. Smith, Calvin Coolidge\nand Julius Rosenwald. will share\nin the distribtuion of $4,600,000\nfrom the estate of the late Conrad\nHubert.\nHubert, inventor of the pocket\nflashlight, died in France three\nyears ago. His will provided that\na committee of prominent citizens\nbe selected to apportion three\nfourths of the estate.\nThe committee finished its work\nsome time ago, and the funds were\nmade available yesterday.\nThe following institutions will\nshare in the $4,600,000:\nScouts Get Million.\nThe Boy Scouts of America; Girl\nSlants, Inc.: St. Vincent's hospital.\nNew York; Provident hospital. Chi\ncago; Beekman Street hospital.\nNew York $500,000 each.\nAmerican National Red Cross\n(for construction of a building for\nthe New York chapter )\u20145375,000.\nY. M. C. A. of Jersey- City; Jew\nish Mental Health society. New\nsork: Hie National Committee for\nMental 1 Hygiene: the Jewish Theo\nlogical Seminary of America: New\nYork university\u2014B2so 000 each.\n8100,000 for Blind.\nThe Children\u2019s Aid society, New\nYork\u2014s2oo,ooo\nUniversity of Chicago 825Q.000.\nBeth Israel hospital. New York^\nHoward university, Washington\u2014\n-8200,000 each.\nPenry Street settlement. New\n5 ork: American Foundation for the\nBlind\u2014sloo,ooo each.\nWhy, Mr. President, in the name of justice or anything else,\nshould workers in no way responsible for this depression, be re\nquired to bear the burden inflicted upon the nation through the\nmaladministration of industry by the large employers? Isn\u2019t it\nobvious that when John Smith, an employed railroad switchman,\ntakes a day\u2019s pay per month out of his meager wage to be given to\nsome man out of a job, he does not increase the sum total of buy\ning power?\nDoesn\u2019t the real solution of the present industrial crisis re\nquire that there be an increase in the purchasing power of the\nmasses? Isn\u2019t it perfectly silly to expect such increase when, for\nthe most part, unemployment relief is coming out of the pockets\nof those who are at work\u2014in many cases at near-starvation wages?\nAnd have you forgotten that relief contributions from the wealthy\ninvariably are passed on in increased costs of commodities to con\nsumers.\nIt seems to us, Mr. President, that you are in th^ position of\nhaving to keep workers loyal to an economic system which is smash-\nFRIDAY EVENING, DECEMBER 19, 1930.\nCOUZENS ASKS\nPROVISO FOR\nLOCAL LABOR\nDemands Residence\nof 90 Days to Share\nEmployment.\nBl THOMAS L. STOKES.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nWASHINGTON\u2014House and sen\nate conferees failed to agree today\non controversial amendments made\nby the senate to the .$116,000,000 un\nemployment reli^ bill.\nSenate conferees held out for the\nCeuzen\u2019s amendment which provides\nthat only local labor of at least 90-\nday residence can be employed on\nprojects financed from the emer\ngency fund. I\nThey also refused to recede from\ntwo local amendments which would\ngrant Alabama and Georgia certain\nfederal aid road funds without re\nquiring state funds to be expended\nin like amount.\nHoover Scores Victory, i\nThe bill again goes back to the\nsenate for consideration.\nIt was understood that the most\nserious i>oint of difference was over\nIhe portion of the Couzen\u2019s amend\nment which provides that not only\nmust local labor be employed but\nthat the highest \u201cprevailing wage\nscale\u201d must be paid.\nPresident. Hoover was victorious\ntoday, in the main, from the bitter\nconflict with congress over unem\nployment and drought relief ap\npropriations.\nWhen the battle ended, it was re\nvealed the president had won on\nthe major points at issue in the two\nmeasures which constitute his re\nlief program. Congress was expect\ned to approvejhem finally today in\nthe form of conference reports,\nadding the last legislative touches\nbefore they are sent to the white\nhouse.\nHouses Reach Compromise.\nThis opens the way for adjourn\nment for Christmas tomorrow night.\nIn the ease of the $116,000,090\nconstruction bill to give jobs to. un\nemployed on rivers and harbors,\nhighways ami flood control projects,\nthe senate yielded to give the presi\ndent discretion in transferring\nfunds from one purpose to another,\nwhich was the principal point at\nissue.\nOn the other measure, that for\ndrought relief, senate and house\nTurn to Page Four, Column One.\n\u25a0What do~\nuou waio?\nis\nSHOPPINg\\w\nPAYS TILL W\n^HR^TMAS/\n/'X iK/^- i? wB ir^' S'\nJF w/7'-wl ^X'^W /jr\nx//# ^i w\u00dfavaWw t\nWix^fc\u00ab\u00bb\n\u2018-ww^ m^L\nfelTinx\nx\\x==k^s^\nllK||||^ttgSira^&^Cw!is^^\nFEAR FOR 200\nON MISSING\nFRENCH SHIP\nALGIERS\u2014The French passen\nger ship El Golea, carrying 200 pas\nsengers from Algiers to Port Ven\nders, France, was overdue tdday in\nthe worst Mediterranean storm in\n35 years.\nHarbor Is Blocked.\nDozens of wireless calls for help\nwere received here from distressed\nvessels, but relief tugs were unable\nto leave Algiers harbor, blocked by\nthe sinking of two tugs and 12\nbarges at the port entrance.\nHeavy rains and cyclones swept\nnorthern Algiers, tearing ships\nfrom their moorings and disrupting\ncommunications over a wide area.\nNo accurate estimate of casual\nties was possible.\nDamage Is Heavy.\nDamage to the port here alone\nwas estimated at 30,000,000 francs\n(about $1,250,000).\nThe storm came after a disas\ntrous seven months\u2019 drought. Dried\nriver beds were soon filled and\nmany streams overflowed. Many\ncattle were reported drowned and\nvineyards were ruined.\nEntered as second-class matter August 25, 1920, at the postoffiee\nat Milwaukee, Wisconsin, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nTHROW OUT THE LIFE LINE!\nYouth Shows\nGood Will in\nForgery Case\nDemonstration of justified faith\nin human nature brought to munic\nipal court today a spirit in har\nmony with the holiday season.\nJohn Ross Halsey, 25 years old, a\nformer Notre Dame university stu\ndent, had been convicted of passing\na worthless .$94 check on a down\ntown hotel.\nHe was sentenced to one to two\nyears in the house of correction\nid was given temporary stay of\nexecution.\nJudge George A. Shaughnessy\nordered him to report to him today.\nThe judge fairly beamed when\nHalsey appeared in court. He in\nformed the judge he has a position\nas a shoe store clerk and that he\nis gradually making restitution of\nthe money obtained ou the check.\nSo pleased was the judge that he\nmade the stay of execution perma\nnent.\n9 Errant Husbands\nFreed in Court\nThe spirit of Christmas permeat\ned municipal court today, when\nTurn to Page Four, Column One.\ning up while unscrupulous employers who profit by this system\nare busily engaged in shoving the same workers farther down in the\neconomic scale by compelling them to contribute to the support of\ntheir brothers out of jobs.\nYou have been press-agented from one end of this country to\nthe other as a great humanitarian and an even greater engineer.\nIf you are what your friends say you are, why don\u2019t you take just\none step which will prove it? At least to those thousands of starv\ning men, women and children who need some kind of proof in the\nform of food for their stomachs, clothing- for their backs and homes\nwherein they may shut out the cold of these winter months.\nWe submit, Mr. President, that it is not an idle use of words\nto urge you to stand for constructive legislation which will help\ntoward restoring prosperity. Because, whether you or Andy Mel\nlon like it or not, legislation is the only practical way out of the\npresent nation-wide dilemma of unemployment\nLet us have a Liberty Loan for the Jobless, Mr. President!\nE. J. COSTELLO, Editor.\nTRAIL BANDITS\nIN SHAMP BY\nDOGS, PLANES\nSAFFORD, Ala.\u2014A pursuit with\nairplanes and bloodhounds was\nbegun today by 150 men who be\nlieved they had surrounded four\nhank bandits in Bogue Chitto\nswamp near here.\nThe bandits robbed the Maticu\nJunction bank of more than .$5,000\nlate yesterday Trailed by a sher\niff\u2019s posse, they abandoned their\nautomobiles and fled into the\nswamps, holding off officers by fire\nfrom automatic rifles.\nBloodhounds sent into the swamp\nto ferret out the men crawled hack\nwounded. Additional dogs were\nbrought f rom Montgomery. Ala., and\nMeridian. Miss., and airplanes vere\nsummoned.\nNational guardsmen from Selma\nand law enforcement officers from\nMontgomery joined the posse today.\nSheriff R. L Hammer, in charge of\nthe hunt, said he expected the band\nits would nut up a determined fight.\nSheriff Hanime said he consid\nered it improbable the bandits had\nesc'n^d from the swamp His men\nTurn to Page Four, Column Four.\nHOME\nEDITION\nPRICE THREE CENTS\nSTIFF BREEZE\nFANS FIRE AT\nWEWOKA, OKLA.\nFire Fighters Use\nPlane to Rush to\nScene.\nWEWOKA, Okla.< Ilie unruly\nDeep Rock Oil Co.'' No. 1 Douglas\nwell of the Wewoka townsite pool\nturned into a blazing torch today,\nthreatening this city of 10,400 per\nsons. Fanned by a stiff breeze from\nthe west, the well fed by 80,000.000\ncubic feet of gas, detied efforts ol\nits crew to control it.\nThe gas well apparently was sei\nafire by a spark, perhaps caused by\nmetal banging together on the steel\nrig.\nThe well came in out of control\nearlier this month. Crews subdued\nit after a week's Lattlj and drilling\noperations were continued after a\nAve-inch casing had lun removed.\nAirplane Is Used.\nFirefighters from Tulsa flew here\nby airplane when the gas caught\nfire today. Drilling operations in\nprolific Wilcox sand area were\nshut down for safety.\nMore than 1,000 feet of drill pipe\nwere thrown from the bore by the\npressure of gas released in the\nblast. Heavy drilling tools were\nscattered over an area of half a\nmile. The gas burned with a ter\nrific roaring. The heat was so in\ntense that workmen could not ap\nproach. Asbestos suits were or\ndered for th^em.\nWater lines were laid for a siege\nto extinguish the flames shooting\nover the derrick into the air.\nThe well came in as a gasser sev\neral weeks ago from a 3,887 feet\ndepth. It produced gas from the\nCromwell sand.\nTanks Are Destroyed.\nIt is one of the drilling operations\nstarted in the townsite field after\nits discovery a few months ago.\nThe well is located more than a\nmile from the city\u2019s residential dis\ntrict.\nThe derrick and storage tanks\nwere reduced to molten metal with\nin an hour after the well caught\nfire.\nWewoka, one of the Udest towns\nin the state, claims more million\naires than any other city of similar\nsize.\nMadison Students\nLeave for Homes\nMADISON \u2014Population of Madi\nson took a sudden drop today as\nthousands of university students de\nparted to spend Christmas holidays\nat their homes in other cities. Spe\ncial trains to Chicago, Milwaukee,\nKansas City, Omaha and Minne\napolis aided the exodus. New York\nstudents chartered a bus.\nWeather\n-toQ) i i mi\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Cloudy to\nnight. probably with snow; tomorrow\npartly cloudy. No decided change in\ntemperature. Moderate to fresh west\nand northwest winds.\nWisconsin: Cloudy tonight, possibly\nsnow in east portion. Somewhat colder\nin northwest portion. Tomorrow partly\ncloudy to cloudy.\nTEMPERATURES.\n1 a. m 311 7 a. m ....27\n3 a. m 30| 8 a. m 29\n3 a. m 291 9 a. m .30\n4 a. m. ........28110 a m ...31\n5 a. m. 28|11 a. m 31\n6 a. m 281 Noon .31\nHumidity: 7 p. m., 90; 7 a. m., 94:\nnoon, 88.\nTemperature 24 hours to midnight:\nMaximum, 34; minimum, 22: mean. 28:\nnormal, 25. Midnight to 10 a. m.: Max\nimum, 31: minimum. 27: relative humid\nity, 94. wind velocity at 7 a. nt., sever,\nmiles; direction of wind at 7 a. m,\nsouthwest; sunrise tod&y, 710; sunset\n4:20.","height":"28962","width":"21501"}}
